funding_code: REAP-MAND RENEW ENERGY SYSTEMS LOANS GUAR
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide permanent debt service for a 6.75MW ground-mounted solar project in Wellsville NY. GSPP 2496 Lewis Road, LLC is one of multiple GSPP commercial-scale solar projects being constructed in NY with the same organizational structure. The solar array is expected to produce 9,964,600 kWh of electricity in the first full year.

naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide working capital for Mary Beckendorf dba Riverview Farms, a pasture raised pig farm located in Fillmore, New York. The grant will provide the funds for Riverview Farms to process their products by a local USDA certified facility and market those products as locally raised food products.

naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 12 new self-contained breathing apparatuses (SCBA) for the Village of Angelica Fire Department located in Allegany County. This equipment will replace the villages old SCBA equipment and additionally serve the towns of Angelica, Allen, West Almond and village of Angelica.

naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to finance the purchase of a 2021 truck with salt dog spreader, snow plow and dump body, and Case 580SN backhoe. This snow plow truck will replace the unreliable 2017 truck and will serve the Village of Bolivar, NY in providing safe and properly maintained streets.

naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new ambulance, specifically a Ford F-450 Type III Medix ambulance. This ambulance will replace the old and unreliable ambulance. The new ambulance will serve the towns of Independence and Willing, located in Allegany County New York, along with the town of West Union, located in Steuben County New York. Having reliable emergency response equipment improves the quality of life in the rural American community.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve approximately 12,900 linear feet of 8-inch water main in the town of Dunkirk Shorewood water district. After the improvements, the water facility will be able to provide safe and reliable potable water supply and fire protection to all residences in the Shorewood water district. A new replacement water distribution network will reduce the operations and maintenance time and increase water quality reliability. The total project costs are $2,295,000, with $6,000 in applicant contribution and $2,289,000 in Rural Development direct loan funds. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to complete a Comprehensive Stormwater Management Improvement project in the Village of Sherman, located in Chautauqua County. This project will benefit village residents by correcting stormwater management issues and improve the health, welfare, and safety of the residents.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create the Van Buren Water District in the town of Pomfret in Chautauqua County. The project will extend public water service to residential homes, commercial properties within the Van Buren Water District. Residents and businesses in the Town of Pomfret, have experienced ongoing difficulties with water main breaks due to the poor condition of the existing mains. To minimize the threats to public health and safety, and in response to a notice of public interest, the Town of Pomfret created the Van Buren water district. The total project costs are $1,838,000 with a direct loan of $1,550,000 and a $288,000 Rural Development grant.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create Sewer District Number 1 in the town of Peru, located in Clinton County, NY. The project is receiving additional funding due to increased costs at bidding. The project will help provide reliable sewer service to town residents. The total project costs are $5,404,024, with a $3,612,000 direct loan obligated in 2018; other funding of $1,007,024 and a subsequent loan of $785,000.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to pay for additional costs incurred for improvements to the Town of Perus Sewer district number 1 in the Town of Peru, which is in Clinton County, New York. The project will improve the North Bend trunk sewer main which will be relocated to an accessible street location. The project will also relocate the Maiden Lane pump station as well as installing two new pump stations along Main Street. A new interceptor main will also be installed. The project will provide reliable sewer service to town residents. The total project costs are $1,029,000 with $1,029,000in Rural Development direct loan funds. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide working capital for Hudson Valley Fish Farm Inc, located in Hudson, New York. The farm uses a recirculating aquaculture system (RAS) to raise steelhead trout on its land-based, commercial-scale facility. New holiday packages will be introduced over the last 12 weeks of 2021, featuring Hudson Valley Fisheries steelhead trout. The holiday packages provide the ingredients for making a great fish entree at home, suitable for special occasions with friends and family. As a result of this investment, 4 jobs will be created. Funding includes a $113,484 Applicant Contribution.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by Syracuse Universitys Center for Sustainable Community Solutions (SU-CSCS) to provide hands-on Sustainable Material Management (SMM) technical assistance and/or training for rural communities throughout NY and Puerto Rico(PR). For rural NY communities the technical training and assistance (TAT) will be delivered through a variety of opportunities including but not limited to meetings, workshops, roundtable discussions, tours, summits and or conferences. SU CSCS will assist organics management professionals and other stakeholders that focus on wasted food reduction, food recovery, organics recycling and compost end-use for soil amendment. For rural PR communities SU CSCS will assist recycling professionals, local elected officials, and stakeholders by developing and administering TAT through their local networks. The total project costs are $309,855 with $33,855 in applicant contribution and $276,000 in Rural Development Solid Waste Management Grant funding. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

naics_description: RESCUE AND AMBULANCE SERVICE - EQUIPMENT BUILDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase four new AW-119Kx helicopters, modified for medical service operation, for Mercy Flight Central, Inc. in Canandaigua, New York. These helicopters will replace the corporations 23 year-old helicopters that are requiring increased maintenance therefore reducing flight numbers. The new helicopters will allow Mercy Flight Central, Inc. to continue to provide critical care and air transport to those patients who are critically ill or injured. Mercy Flight Central serves over 13 New York state counties. Total project costs are $21,130,344 with an applicant contribution of $3,146,344, an RD CF loan of $8,992,000 and an RD guaranteed CF loan of $8,992,000.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to allow the completion of a Preliminary Engineering Report to be prepared with recommendations for the Town of Bristol, which is located in Ontario county, New York . The study will look at the Day Road Water Tank for permanent, long-term solutions to reduce disinfection byproducts formed in the system. The solution will include ways to reduce trihalomethanes to compliance within current regulations. The recommendations will benefit both the Town of Bristol Water District No. 1 as well as the Canandaigua-Bristol Water District - as both are in the service area. Total project costs are $30,000 with $8,000 in applicant contribution and $22,000 in Rural Development pre-development grant funds. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

The new pipeline will connect the towns existing water distribution main with water supplied by the Oswego County Water Authority.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to pay for additional costs incurred to construct a Childrens Specialty Hospital in the Town of Thompson, which is located in Sullivan county, New York. New York State does not currently have any short-term inpatient assessment programs for children with complex developmental disabilities, including Autism Spectrum Disorders and medical frailties. Recognizing these challenges, The Center for Discovery (TCFD) is building a Childrens Specialty Hospital to provide a short-term clinical assessment program with the goal of better diagnosing underlying problems that affect behavior and learning. Development of the Childrens Specialty Hospital will service and have a direct impact on rural communities without access to specialized care, including, but not limited to, Sullivan, Delaware, Chenango, Otsego, Columbia, Ulster, Orange, Greene, Broome and Schoharie counties. TCFD is a not-for-profit agency dedicated to the enrichment of the lives of people with intellectual disabilities. TCFD provides educational, clinical, and residential services for intellectually disabled individuals. The Agency is the largest private sector employer in Sullivan County, N.Y. Total project costs are $48,570,000 with $3,000,000 in Rural Development direct loan funds, $35,000,000 in previously funded Rural Development Community Facility loan funds, $5,000,000 in a previously funded guaranteed loan with Sterling National Bank and $5,570,000 in previously funded other grants. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

project_announced_description: This USDA Rural Development Investment will be used improve the Cherry Creek sanitary sewer system in the town of Cherry Creek. The improvements include the construction of a parallel rotating biological contactor unit to provide enhanced biological treatment and the refurbishing of the existing rotating biological contactor unit. Additionally, the primary tank will be rehabilitated, process pumps and Variable Frequency Drives will be installed as well as a new post-aeration blower will be installed. The collection system pump stations and infrastructure will be improved to extend the life of these critical assets. Total project costs are $4,573,000 with $2,000,000 in EPA grant funding, $1,573,000 in Rural Development direct loan funds and $1,000,000 in Rural Development grant funds.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a salt storage building in the town of Ellenburg, which is located in Clinton County, New York. This building will be used to protect the sand and salt used on town roads during winter storms. This building will result in approximately 6,300 cubic yards of available storage and will include a clearance to allow for inside dumping of large-payload dump trucks. The building will improve efficiency of winter road maintenance and will also improve the environment by eliminating runoff from the existing outdoor storage pile.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide hands-on Sustainable Material Management (SMM) technical assistance and/or training for rural communities throughout New York and Puerto Rico by the Syracuse University Center for Sustainable Community Solutions (SU-CSCS). For rural NY communities, the technical training and assistance (TAT) will be delivered through a variety of opportunities including but not limited to: meetings, workshops, roundtable discussions, tours, summits and or conferences. SU-CSCS will assist organics management professionals and other stakeholders that focus on wasted food reduction, food recovery, organics recycling and compost end-use for soil amendment. For rural Puerto Rican communities, SU-CSCS will assist recycling professionals, local elected officials, and stakeholders by developing and administering TAT through their local networks. The total project costs are $264,500 with $26,600 in applicant contribution and $237,900 in Rural Development Solid Waste Energy Grant. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance and/or training for rural communities throughout New York and Puerto Rico for water resources management. The program developed by Syracuse University Center will include technical training and individualized assistance to rural communities focused on integrated water, waste water, storm-water, and rural infrastructure planning, using models for sustainable economic development through infrastructure finance, watershed management, flood and drought resiliency, and disaster preparedness. The total project costs are $147,200 with $147,200 in Rural Development Technical Assistance and Training grant. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct needed upgrades to the village sewer system in the village of Dundee, which is located in Yates County, New York. The project will address all operational and regulatory concerns with the current waste water treatment plant and involves the installation of a new Sequencing Batch Reactor (SBR) treatment system housed in a new concrete tank. The system will be completely automated and require less operator input. The total project costs are $17,798,000 with $250 in applicant contribution, a $2,057,750 Water Infrastructure Improvement Act (WIIA) grant, a $268,000 Water Quality Improvement Project (WQIP) grant $8,500,000 in Rural Development direct loan funds and $6,972,000 in Rural Development grant funds. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

program: Rural Energy for America Technical Assistance Grant Program
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: OTHER SCIENTIFIC AND TECHNICAL CONSULTING SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to agricultural producers applying for the renewable energy assistance program (REAP) grants. Priority will be given to applicants in distressed/disadvantaged communities, those pursuing projects using underutilized technologies, and those pursuing projects under $20,000. The New York State Energy Research and Development Authority (NYSERDA) offers information and analysis, programs, technical expertise, and funding for residents to increase energy efficiency, save money, use renewable energy, and reduce their reliance on fossil fuels. NYSERDA will use the REAP technical assistance grant (TAG) funds to roll out the New York Agricultural Producers REAP Technical Assistance Program (RTAP). The purpose of both programs is to increase the number of energy efficiency improvements by agricultural producers in the state to ensure the long-term sustainability and viability of New York farms, and to help meet state and national climate goals. Specifically, it is expected that 136 New York agricultural producers will receive funding through RTAP to enhance their REAP grant applications.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create a water district in the town of Waterloo in Seneca County, New York. No other funding sources have been identified for this project.

naics_industry_sector: Administrative and Support and Waste Management and Remediation Services (56)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to provide technical assistance in the form of marketing and outreach for the Catskill Cuisine Phase 2 event and winter promotional weekends. The Sullivan Catskills Visitors Association (SCVA) is the official destination management organization for Sullivan county, New York. Established in 1997, the organization works with a wide variety of local, state, regional, national and international partners to strategically increase visitation and visitor spending that will create economic growth and stability in Sullivan county. naics_industry_sector: Administrative and Support and Waste Management and Remediation Services (56)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to fund the Sullivan Catskills Purveyor Marketplace, a business opportunity and development initiative that will feature local rural businesses in a retail marketplace open up to 12 times a year. The marketplace will be created on the main floor of the Liberty Mall, in Liberty, New York, which has been vacant for over a decade. This initiative will empower local rural purveyors to showcase and sell their products to the public pre-holiday, during shoulder seasons and summer peak tourism seasons. Sullivan County Visitors Association was established in 1997 to coordinate local economic development activities in Sullivan county to align with the New York State Division of Tourism marketing initiatives. Funding includes a $30,000 Applicant Contribution.

naics_industry_sector: Administrative and Support and Waste Management and Remediation Services (56)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to provide technical assistance in creating organized thematic pre-scheduled tours for visitors throughout the Catskills region in Sullivan county, New York. Tours will also cater to families with members who have developmental disabilities. The objective will be to bring people directly to the front steps of local rural businesses as well as create jobs by training locals to become ambassador guides on the tours. Sullivan County Visitors Association was established in 1997 to coordinate local economic development activities in Sullivan county to align with the New York State Division of Tourism marketing initiatives.

Visitors will be able to experience outdoor adventures, local farms, state trails, parks, fishing venues, and shop at rural businesses. The Sullivan Catskills Visitors Association (SCVA) is the official destination management organization for Sullivan county, New York. naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to pay for additional costs incurred to construct a childrens specialty hospital in the town of Thompson, Sullivan County, New York. New York State does not currently have any short-term inpatient assessment programs for children with complex developmental disabilities, including Autism Spectrum Disorders and medical frailties. Recognizing these challenges, The Center for Discovery (TCFD) is building a childrens specialty hospital to provide a short-term clinical assessment program with the goal of better diagnosing underlying problems that affect behavior and learning. Development of the Childrens Specialty Hospital will service and have a direct impact on rural communities without access to specialized care, including, but not limited to: Sullivan, Delaware, Chenango, Otsego, Columbia, Ulster, Orange, Greene, Broome and Schoharie counties. TCFD is a not-for-profit agency dedicated to the enrichment of the lives of people with intellectual disabilities and will provide educational, clinical, and residential services for intellectually disabled individuals. TCFD is the largest private sector employer in the county.
